00;">bow out</a> at the peak of her powers.<br/><br/>Ironically, even as ca=
lls for generational change rip through the Democratic Party, it seems obvi=
ous that Shaheen would have made life easier for them if she <em>had</em> d=
ecided to run again. An open seat Senate race in Shaheen=E2=80=99s increasi=
ngly red-leaning home state will jangle Democratic nerves
and stress their campaign funds. And the state=E2=80=99s Republican bench i=
s fearsome: Contenders include Shaheen=E2=80=99s 2014-era rival <strong>Sco=
tt Brown</strong> and former Gov. <strong>Chris Sununu</strong>. On the Dem=
 side, U.S. Rep. <strong>Chris Pappas</strong> is making lots of noise abou=
t running, and retired Rep. <strong>Annie Kuster</strong>=E2=80=99s name ha=
s also bounced around in the past 36 hours.<br/><br/>This is going to becom=
e a recurring headache for the party as its members age out. Democratic
colleagues <strong>Tina Smith</strong> of Minnesota and <strong>Gary Peters=
</strong> of Michigan, ages 67 and 66 respectively, have also said they won=
=E2=80=99t stand for reelection. (All eyes are now on Senate Minority Whip<=
strong> Dick Durbin</strong>, 80, of Illinois.) So far, though, Peters is t=
he only one vacating a Democratic Senate seat in a state that Trump won in =
2024.</li><li style=3D"Margin:0 0 24px 0;"><em>Speaking of generational cha=
nge=E2=80=A6</em>: Intriguingly, <strong>Pete Buttigieg</strong>
<em>won=E2=80=99t</em> be joining the Michigan Senate fray, having taken hi=
mself out of the running for Peters=E2=80=99s seat in what was widely portr=
ayed as a missed opportunity for Democrats. (There=E2=80=99s speculation he=
 could be eyeing the White House instead.) Nevertheless, Buttigieg could ha=
ve had an incredibly difficult campaign: He moved to the state not three ye=
ars ago, after branding himself as <em>the </em>mayor of South Bend=E2=80=
=A6 Indiana. And the potential Michigan bid seemed particularly opportunist=
ic, given that there was little chance he would have ever gotten elected st=
atewide in Indiana. Granted, different states have different tolerance for =
carpet-bagging:
It worked for <strong>Romney </strong>and <strong>Clinton </strong>(born in=
 Michigan and Illinois, respectively), although not for Scott Brown, who ra=
n against Shaheen after losing reelection across state lines in Massachuset=
ts.<br/><br/>Anyway, both parties have stacked farm teams in Michigan. On t=
he Republican side, there are sitting U.S. Representatives <strong>John Jam=
es </strong>and<strong> Bill Huizenga</strong>, along with 2024 Republican =
